<paragraph xmlns:gate="http://www.gate.ac.uk" gate:gateId="0" gate:annotMaxId="165">Aeschbacher, Niklaus, Swiss conductor; <Event_Birth gate:gateId="164" RE="April 30, 1917" Pred="birth" Pred-tyoe="time"><Birth gate:gateId="162" predict="birth">b.</Birth> Trogen, <Date gate:gateId="129" rule1="DateNameRev" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">April 30, 1917</Date></Event_Birth>. He studied in <Location gate:gateId="130" rule1="InLoc1" locType="city" rule2="LocFinal">Zurich</Location> and <Location gate:gateId="131" rule1="Location1" locType="city" rule2="LocFinal">Berlin</Location>. Was active as theater conductor in <Location gate:gateId="132" rule1="InLoc1" locType="country" rule2="LocFinal">Germany</Location>; appointed conductor of the Municipal Theater in <Location gate:gateId="133" rule1="InLoc1" locType="city" rule2="LocFinal">Bern</Location> in <Date gate:gateId="134" rule1="YearContext1" kind="date" rule2="DateOnlyFinal">1949</Date>. He wrote a radio opera Die roten Schuhe (<Date gate:gateId="135" rule1="TempYear1" kind="date" rule2="YearOnlyFinal">1943</Date>) and chamber music. </paragraph>